FBIS3-45560 "drchi009_a_94014" FBIS-CHI-94-009 Document Type:Daily Report 13 January 1994 INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS General Foreign Economic Aid For 1993 Summarized HK1301121994 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1334 GMT 12 Jan 94 HK1301121994 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Beijing, January 11 (CNS)--China continued to extend its economic assistance to developing countries in Asia, Africa, Latin America and the South Pacific region in 1993. A total of 272 items of foreign aid were carried out by China in 72 countries last year with their accomplishment described as sound. The foreign aid covered 77 complete sets of items and 113 joint- ventured items involving technological cooperation. Eighty-two items were considerered preparatory for construction while 16 items were completed. Foreign aid items undertaken in Bangladesh, Burma, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Mongolia, Cameroon and Ethiopia, including construction of bridges, railways, a water supply project and an agricultural items, showed sound economic and social results. Nineteen new items covering a cement factory, a hospital, a highway, an acupuncture and moxibustion center, and a housing item started last year in such countries as Peru, Sudan, Burundi, Tunisia, Namibia and Mauritius. China employed various patterns in its foreign aid including a combination of foreign assistance and cooperation of mutual interest in order to push forward direct cooperation between China's enterprises and those of the countries receiving assistance. A total of 45 items were carried out in 24 countries assisted by using such a pattern. The number of contracts signed for such items between the parties concerned was put at 12. China also offered some 50 batches of material aid to some developing countries in 1993 while at the same time striking cooperation with United Nations agencies involving cooperative activities between developing countries, offering them help.
